  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The prayer which Jehoshaphat directed to Jahve the God of the fathers, as the almighty Ruler over all kingdoms, consists of a short representation of the circumstances of the case. Jahve had given the land to His people Israel for an everlasting possession, and Israel had built a sanctuary to His name therein (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 20:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 20:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); but they had in no way provoked the Ammonites, Moabites, and Edomites to fall upon them, and to drive them out of their land (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 20:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 20:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). On these two facts Jehoshaphat founds his prayer for help, in a twofold manner: in respect to the first, calling to mind the divine promise to hear the prayers offered up to God in the temple (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 20:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); and in reference to the second, laying emphasis upon the inability of Israel to fight against so numerous an enemy (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 20:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). In his manner of addressing Jahve, \"God of our fathers,\" there is contained a reason why God should protect His people in their present distress. Upon Him, who had given the land to the fathers for a possession, it was incumbent to maintain the children in the enjoyment of it, if they had not forfeited it by their sins. Now Jahve as a covenant God was bound to do this, and also as God and ruler of heaven and earth He had the requisite power and might; cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 115:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". להתיצּב עמּך אין, there is none with Thee who could set himself, i.e., could withstand Thee: cf. the similar phrase, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 14:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and for the thought, see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Chronicles 29:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". - On ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 20:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
